Index sort feature selection

Identifying discriminative features on index sort data

library(randomForest)
library(randomForestExplainer)
library(readr)
library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
library(smotefamily)
library(GGally)
theme_set(theme_bw())
set.seed(1234)


# load data
dat = read_csv('data/example.csv')
head(dat, n=10)

# what do the feature distributions look like?
ggpairs(dat, aes(color=as.factor(Colony), alpha=0.1))

# subsample data
n.colonies = sum(dat$Colony==1)
dat.positive = subset(dat, Colony==1)
dat.negative = dat[sample(which(dat$Colony==0), size=n.colonies),]
dat.subsampled = rbind(dat.positive, dat.negative)

# augment data; adjust K as appropriate
dat.augmented = SMOTE(select(dat, -Colony), K=3, dat$Colony)$dat

# train bagging model
rf.augmented = randomForest(as.factor(class)~., data=dat.augmented, mtry=ncol(dat.augmented)-1, localImp=TRUE, ntree=100)

# get depth distribution of features
mindepth = min_depth_distribution(rf.augmented)

# histograms of depth distributions; lower depth indicates a more discriminative feature
mindepth %>% ggplot(aes(x=minimal_depth)) + geom_bar() + facet_grid(variable~.) + labs(title='Depth distribution for bagging model')

# boxplot of depth distributions; lower depth indicates a more discriminative feature
mindepth %>% ggplot(aes(x=variable, y=minimal_depth)) + geom_boxplot() + labs(title='Depth distribution for bagging model') + scale_y_continuous(trans = "reverse")
